SIMPLE: navy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Navy
<hw>Na"vy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Navies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[ OF. <ets>navie</ets>, fr.
L. <ets>navis</ets> ship. See <er>Nave</er> of a church.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A fleet of ships; an assemblage of merchantmen, or so
many as sail in company.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>navy</xex> also of Hiram,
that brought gold from Ophir.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>1 kings x.
11.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The whole of the war vessels belonging to a nation
or ruler, considered collectively; <as>as, the <ex>navy</ex> of
Italy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The officers and men attached to the war vessels of
a nation; <as>as, he belongs to the <ex>navy</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>same as <er>navy blue</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Navy bean</b></col>. <cd>see <er>Bean</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Navy yard</b></col>, <cd>a place set apart as a shore station
for the use of the navy. It often contains all the mechanical and other
appliences for building and equipping war vessels and training their
crews.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Navy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Navy
<hw>Na"vy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a color of navy
blue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Navy blue</ent>⟦br⟧
